While the mayoral hopefuls were opining on the fate of the kittens, August and Arthur were recuperating at an Animal Care & Control shelter in the East New York section of Brooklyn.

Sources told the Post that the 8-week-old pets have been kept together as they are undergoing physical and behavioral tests.

August and Arthur, each weighing around 2lbs, will be vaccinated and then transferred to a foster home. Within a couple of weeks, they will be available for adoption.

When the two tiny felines were spotted frolicking on the train tracks near the Church Avenue station in Brooklyn about 11am, Metropolitan Transportation Authority workers turned off the power.

Passengers on the B and Q lines were stranded for about two hours while police officers chased the cats down the tracks.

